..TEXT:
|se dritta o torta va~: Cf. ^Inf.~ I, 3; ^Par.~
XXVI, 62.  |non~ @e ^suo merto~: "Merto" (^merito~) is "desert" of
punishment or of reward; cf. vs. 60, "merto di lode o di biasmo,"
and "meritare" as used in vs. 65.  See Dante's ^Letter to Can
Grande~ (^Epist.~ XIII, 25), where this principle of reward and
punishment is referred to as the allegorical subject of the poem:
"Subiectum est homo prout merendo et demerendo per arbitrii
libertatem iustitie premiandi et puniendi obnoxius est."  ("The
subject is `man, as by good or ill deserts, in the exercise of
the freedom of his choice, he becomes liable to rewarding or
punishing justice.'")
