..TEXT:
|Quest'@e 'l principio... voi~: Thus Virgil
comes to the conclusion which is the answer to Dante's main
point, expressed in vs. 45.  See ^Conv.~ IV, ix, 7, where Dante
writes:
..TEXT:
<<<FORMATTING-OFF>>>
     Sono anche operazioni che la nostra [ragione] considera
     ne l'atto de la volontade, s@i come offendere e giovare, s@i
     come star fermo e fuggire a la battaglia, s@i come stare
     casto e lussuriare, e queste del tutto soggiacciono a la
     nostra volontade; e per@o semo detti da loro buoni e rei,
     perch'elle sono proprie nostre del tutto, perch@e, quanto la
     nostra volontade ottenere puote, tanto le nostre operazioni
     si stendono.
..TEXT:
<<<FORMATTING-OFF>>>
     There are also operations which our reason considers as they
     exist in the act of will, such as attacking and succouring,
     standing ground or fleeing in battle, abiding chaste or
     wantoning; and these are entirely subject to our will, and
     therefore we are considered good or bad on their account,
     because they are properly ours in their entirety; for, so
     far as our will can have its way, so far do operations that
     are really ours extend.
